                            <comment id="15209194" author="misty" created="Wed, 23 Mar 2016 21:18:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-11960&quot; title=&quot;Provide a sample to show how to use Thrift client authentication&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-11960&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-11960&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; has a demo client that might be useful&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15209215" author="jinghe" created="Wed, 23 Mar 2016 21:32:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Linked to &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-13116&quot; title=&quot;Enhance the documentation for usage of &amp;quot;doAs&amp;quot; through REST and Thrift gateways&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-13116&quot;&gt;HBASE-13116&lt;/a&gt;. There may be some overlap.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15290040" author="misty" created="Wed, 18 May 2016 23:01:56 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;HBase has a secure Thrift demo client you can reuse - the specific change for secure connections being that you need to use a SASL transport: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/cloudera/hbase/blob/cdh5.4.1-release/hbase-examples/src/main/java/org/apache/hadoop/hbase/thrift/DemoClient.java#L116-L129&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/cloudera/hbase/blob/cdh5.4.1-release/hbase-examples/src/main/java/org/apache/hadoop/hbase/thrift/DemoClient.java#L116-L129&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Apache Thrift only recently added inbuilt support for SASL transports in Python libraries, via &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-1719&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-1719&lt;/a&gt;. I don&apos;t have a direct reference simple-demo, but the key change between secured and insecure connections via thrift -&amp;gt; hbase is to switch the transport into the SASL mode, keeping all else the same. Following the same philosophy as the Java one will work out in Python if you use 0.9.2 Apache Thrift python libraries with its Python+SASL features.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;</comment>
